# @node-versions: v26.1.0
# @description: Wire smol sources, libcompression/IOKit links, glibc compat, and QUIC gate flips into node.gyp
#
# Integrates Socket Security's source files into the Node.js build system
# along with the platform-specific link wiring needed by those sources.
#
# Source files are split into categories:
# 1. Core sources (always compiled): VFS, file I/O, HTTP, SIMD, WebStreams, ILP, FFI
# 2. Optional modules (build flags): PostgreSQL (node_use_postgres), io_uring (node_use_iouring)
# 3. LIEF-dependent sources (node_use_lief): SEA config, binject, bin-infra
#
# Compression: macOS uses libcompression, Linux/Windows use zstd + libdeflate.
# libcompression added to every target linking libnode.a (cctest, embedtest,
# mksnapshot). bcrypt.lib added on Windows for SHA-256 hashing in
# smol_segment.c (BCrypt* functions).
#
# IOKit framework: power_mac.cc calls IOPSGetPowerSourceDescription, so the
# IOKit framework is linked on every macOS target consuming libnode.a (gyp
# does not forward `libraries` from a static_library to its consumers, so
# each consumer mirrors the framework link).
#
# glibc compat: defines a minimal compat layer for the cares/getrandom path
# so the resulting binary tolerates older glibc.
#
# QUIC gates: the two upstream condition blocks that pull node_quic_sources
# into libnode and cctest now gate on node_use_node_quic instead of
# node_use_quic — the configure.py rewrite emits both variables in lockstep
# so legacy third-party gyp files keep working but upstream's ngtcp2 /
# src/quic stack is excluded from the build graph by default. The smol-side
# compile wiring (lsquic + ls-qpack sources + node:smol-quic /
# node:smol-http3 binding glue) lands alongside the JS module-map work.
#
